history.content: 70 is very difficult and requires a lot of time if you don't have much mathematical maturity. 61b and 16b also have pretty large time commitments. I personally would recommend that you take 61b and 16b and maybe one of 53/54 together.

children.subject: i took 70, 61b and 16a (which is significantly easier than 16b) and it was completely doable

Don't, not unless you have a good reason to.

I haven't taken 16B, but cs70 and 61b are both very hard and time intensive. Unless you have a good reason to take both at the same time, there is no reason to burden yourself unnecessarily.

I took something kind of similar (70 61B and EE 40) and it was pretty hellish.To be fair, I do have a hard time thinking about discrete math problems (had a similar issue in CS 170), and EE 40 was just a terrible class overall. 16B I've heard is much better than 40, so I guess you're ok on that part.

Also if you're comfortable with the level of thinking 70 requires you to have then I guess you can try it out, but I'd still suggest that you try a slightly easier combination of classes.
This is somewhat relevant, I'm taking 61A and 70 both right now (freshman) and it is definitely manageable. It really depends on your CS and math background though.

My background:

EE16b - basic linear algebra. almost nothing on circuits. Absolutely nothing on fourier transforms, svd, etc.

61b - did AP CS in high school, so I was okay on the java stuff. However, the algorithms were new to me.

70 - almost nothing on logic. I was walking in cold.

I did CS70, EE16b, and CS61b spring 2016.

Some notes:

1. I did the no-homework option for CS70. Make sure that you stay on top of things if you're going to be lazy like me.

2. Even then it was hellish. Doable but hellish.

3. EE16b has likely gotten easier since then. I don't think they really knew what they were doing last semester.
